Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"(*", "\"\< \[IndentingNewLine]\nWe have now determined \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(x\), \(\[Mu]\)]\)(0) and a suitable contour for the \
instantons\ncorresponding to the saddle-point values of the momenta, \
p=\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(p\), \(s\)]\) and q=\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(q\), \
\(s\)]\). \[IndentingNewLine]\nThe next step is to compute the exponential \
part of the amplitude using \[Psi]Eq,\nthe functional determinant using \
deltaEq, and the spin prefactor using spinExpEq.\[IndentingNewLine]\nThis \
yields M(\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(p\), \(s\)]\),\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(q\), \
\(s\)]\)). We can then approximate M(p,q) away from \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(p\), \
\(s\)]\) and \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(q\), \(s\)]\) by expanding the exponent\nto \
quadratic order around the saddle point. We refer to this as the \
quadratic-instanton approximation. \n\n\>\"", "*)"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9910253936287117`*^9, 3.991025493461445*^9}, {
   3.99102552706439*^9, 3.9910257082454777`*^9}, {3.99102595859499*^9, 
